        E.  Perform pulmonary ventilation by use of lower airway multi-lumen adjuncts,
            the esophageal airway, perilaryngeal airways, stomal intubation, adult oral
            endotracheal intubation, and Continuous Positive Airway Pressure (CPAP).
        F.  Perform percutaneous needle cricothyroidotomy.
        G.  Institute intravenous (IV) catheters saline locks, needles, or other cannulae
            (IV lines), in peripheral veins; and monitor and administer medications
            through pre-existing vascular access.
        H.  Institute intraosseous needles or catheters for infusions.
        I.  Administer intravenous or intraosseous glucose solutions or isotonic
            balanced salt solutions.
        J.  Obtain venous blood samples.
        K.  Perform Valsalva’s maneuver.
        L.  Perform needle thoracostomy.
        M. Monitor thoracostomy tubes.
        N.  Monitor IV solutions containing potassium < 20 mEq/L.
        O.  Use laboratory devices, including point of care testing, for pre-hospital
            screening use to measure lab values including, but not limited to: glucose,
            capnometry, capnography, and carbon monoxide when appropriate
            authorization is obtained from State and Federal agencies, including from the
            Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services pursuant to the Clinical
            Laboratory Improvement Amendments (CLIA).
        P.  Administer approved medications by the following routes: IV, IO,
            intramuscular, subcutaneous, inhalation, transcutaneous, rectal, sublingual,
            endotracheal, intranasal, oral or topical.
        Q.  Administer, using prepackaged products when available, the following
            medications:
            1)     25% and 50% Dextrose;
            2)     Adenosine;
            3)     Aerosolized or nebulized beta-2 specific bronchodilators;
            4)     Aspirin;
            5)     Atropine sulfate;
            6)     Calcium chloride;
            7)     Diphenyhydramine hydrochloride;
            8)     Dopamine hydrochloride;
            9)     Epinephrine;
            10)    Fentanyl;
            11)    Glucagon;
            12)    Lidocaine Hydrochloride;




